Tuesday, January 1, 1963

A little bibliographic work this morning but spend most of the day watching T.V.; first the Rose Parade; then the various bowl football games. The V.S.C.-Wisconsin game had a very close and exciting finish, and wore me out. Checked Christmas cards in the evening.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 07/09/2014 04:34 PM
  • summarsr 03/21/2013 09:56 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:06 PM

Wednesday, January 2, 1963

At the office this morning. Conference at some length with Hi Dillin and F.R. Raymond on certain matters of publicity hinging on the recent F.P.E. El Paso note decisions.

Went over to Arey-Jones from whom had ordered a "National" Diary similar to the ones I have used for many years. Although ordered at least a month ago, it still hadn't arrived, so I decided to change to a "standard" which all the stationers seem to handle now.

Went around to the banks and had my savings accounts balanced, as required for income tax returns. Also made deposits.

Graydon Hoffman came in for a short conference this morning.

Took Larry and Gracie to dinner at the Chuck Wagon tonight.

Worked quite late formulating the basic data for the panel at Rotary tomorrow. My part is the economic situation in the community.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 07/09/2014 04:36 PM

Thursday, January 3, 1963

At the office this morning. Spent all the time getting ready for the ??? panel program at Rotary and accumulated a first-class set of statistics on San Diego's present and future economic situation.

Carl Ritter of the Union called up and gave me a few questions he proposed to ask.

But the actual meeting, as far as my part was concerned, was largely gags. I was badly handicapped by not being able to hear or understand Ritter's questions. So most of my preparation went down the drain. I got some good laughs, but certainly I didn't tell anyone anything of importance.

Went to the bank and did some shopping after the meeting, so it was after 3 when I got home, and was quite tired out.

Notes:

summarsr

Unsure about 1st paragraph, 3rd line "??? panel program"

Friday, January 4, 1963

At the office this morning.

Got some bibliographic work done with chemical abstracts.

Accounts most of the afternoon and evening. They were tangled and hard to straighten out.

Larry came down for awhile this afternoon.

Saturday, January 5, 1963

Letters and bibliographic work today.

Had a talk with Phil 11-12. Also watched the Senior Bowl game for awhile. An exciting finish.

Then back to bibliography and other miscellaneous items.

Larry came down to say goodbye. He returns to Stanford tomorrow.

Sunday, January 6, 1963

Got up this morning at 3:30 to work on the bibliography. Worked until 5:15. Continued work later in the morning.

Went out to Ned Price's place in Rancho Santa Fe for lunch. The Episcopalian minister and his wife also there. Ned has a wonderful country place.

Dinner tonight at the Coronado Hotel with Col + Mrs Kelly of Buffalo. Other guests the Beckers and Halls.

Monday, January 7, 1963

At the office this morning.

Philip started work for the company this morning. I got the first telephone call intended for him, an event that will be duplicated many times in the future.

Hi Dillin showed me an article from a recent Los Angeles Times listing the officers of the principal California utilities. They had me placed as Chairman of the Board of the gas co., - a very unfortunate and disconcerting entry. I could see Hi didn't like it.

Received today from Dr. Henry M. Parrish a complete set of his snake-bite papers down to date, including some not yet published. This is a very important acquisition.

Worked on the Bibliography today and made good gains.

Called Phil and talked over the events of the first day with him.

Tonight I finished the first long-hand draft of the bibliography. Of course there will be additions, but it is ready for copying if necessary.

Tuesday, January 8, 1963

Got up at 3:30 this morning and worked until 5 on the bibliography.

At the office this morning.

Conference with Hi Dillin on Public Utility Commission business for an hour.

Again worked on bibliography today, particularly on the Parrish acquisition and made considerable progress.

At the office this morning.

Briefed some Parrish papers.

Wrote several letters.

Got a lot done on the Parrish papers today.

Thursday, January 10, 1963

At the office this morning.

Went through Chemical Abstracts, vol 55, July-Dec. 1961. Have already been through vol. 56. I will not do any more of these. The articles with very few exceptions, are too technical to be of use to me.

Went over to the Public Library and tried to get a lead to the Reuss paper, but no luck the magazine does not seem to be listed in the Union List of Periodicals.

Went through the Renders Guide to Periodical Literature from March 55 down to date. All but a few of the articles cited are either in Outdoor Life or the Science News Letter. The field covered seems restricted to a few popular magazines. I made a list of those that may have some value so I can follow them up.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 07/09/2014 04:53 PM
  • summarsr 03/22/2013 11:00 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:06 PM

Friday, January 11, 1963

At the office for a short time this morning. Phil dropped in for a chat.

Meeting of the Library Commission from 10 to 11:45.

This afternoon I went to the County Medical Society Library and worked there from 1 to 3:45. Went over the recent copies of the Index Medicus.

Also the Current List of the Medical Literature of the Armed Forces Medical Library in Washington. From these I got some good leads. I think I now have, or will have when I have read these references, enough items for the bibliography as far as Chapters 11-13 inclusive are concerned. The references from these two serials ran from 1956 to 1961 inclusive.

Tonight organized the material I got today.

Saturday, January 12, 1963

Went over to the Natural History Museum and worked in the library for a couple of hours, but didn't get far as the librarian was not on duty and I couldn't find the serials I sought. It was disquieting to run into a good item purely by chance.

Went to the Zoo and autographed a set of Rattlesnakes for David O Scott.

The rest of the day I worked arranging more bibliographic items to check; also called for Amy Lamberton at the airport.

Sunday, January 13, 1963

Today, distressed by the purely accidental discovery of the Fitch paper containing pertinent data in rattlers yesterday, I decided to give the Zoological Record another going over. I had previously surveyed the Record only in the subject index looking for rattler items. Today I went over the Record for 1955-1958, the only volumes available to me at home, and went through the author index, making slips for all those that might contain worthwhile rattler material. This was a big job but I got through with it despite some diversionary chores: Took Janet to Sunday School; called on Phil and discussed some of his newly acquired problems; Minton Fotler called to discuss Zoo business; and Allan and Jean came down to see a repeat of the Jackie Kennedy tour of the White House on T.V. But still I finished making the slips for the Zool. Record articles. Next I shall have to see what I have in my own library and plan to get the rest as I can in the Medical & Natural History Libraries.

Worked late tonight and got all the bibliographical ready for a real campaign. This was a real productive day. Once more I am a little encouraged.

Monday, January 14, 1963

At the office this morning. Various chores; Bohemian Bakery to get some stuff for Larry.

Spent 2 1/2 hours this afternoon at the Natural History Library and checked the Zoological Record for 1959, which is the latest available.

Tuesday, January 15, 1963

At the office this morning. Wrote several important letters; also did some bibliographic work.

Heard this afternoon that our erstwhile gardener Jose Felix Manuelo who ran off with $50 that gg had advanced for the purchase of a lawn mower was shot and wounded at Rosarita Beach by Danny Sanchez, a friend who was frequently around here in contact with Joe.

Went to a San Diego Symphony concert tonight; Berlioz Dramatie Symphony "Romeo and Juliet."

Wednesday, January 16, 1963

At the office this morning.

Made some bibliographic progress today, but not as much as I had hoped; always interruptions.

Wilmer Tanner called from Provo, Utah this afternoon. He had lost the letter I had written requesting an insert in Herpetologica asking for rattler photos. So I had to go down to the office and make copies of the letter which were sent to him by airmail.

Thursday, January 17, 1963

Went to a meeting of the State of California Air Pollution Control Board this morning 9:30 to 12:50. Was impressed by the highly technical and serious study of the problems of moving vehicles. Askem is chairman.

Then to the office for a brief time. Rested most of the afternoon.

Worked on the bibliography tonight and made quite a bit of progress.

Friday, January 18, 1963

Conference with Dillin, Sinnott, and Zitlau from 9 to 10:15 on interconnections. Then with Phil for a half hour or more.

Some shopping.

Baby sitting this afternoon.

Dinner at Lupe for 22 people tonight.

Saturday, January 19, 1963

Worked on bibliographic projects almost all day and made good progress.

Heard from the Press today; the contract as submitted is satisfactory.

Scholia meeting tonight; Ned Price talked on the European Common Market, a lively discussion.

Last filling of my Cad: 144 miles/18.4 gals = 7.8 m.p.g

Sunday, January 20, 1963

More bibliographic work today. Fair progress.

Joe Copp came around and worked on his reproduction project in the library. Took quite a bit of my time running items down for him.

Also Ricky Klautz came around for material on goldsmith.

At the office this morning.

Meeting of Executive Committee, 10 to 12; followed by Board of Directors 12-2:30.

Miscellaneous work this afternoon.

Tuesday, January 22, 1963

This morning at 7:15 went out to a breakfast at Torrey Pines Lodge with Dr. George Lindsay. The purpose was a meeting of the Greater San Diego Industry Education Council; I was there in the place of Norman Lawson to accept a citation given to the Natural History Museum. There were business sessions and a talk by Dr. Herbert C. York on the present status of the University of California and its future expansion, especially the La Jolla branch. This was quite interesting but I didn't get down to the office until nearly eleven.

Baby-sat this afternoon.

Meeting of the trustees of the 300. 5:30 to 9-. They oked the contract for the publication of Rattlesnakes, second printing, with the U.C. Press.

This morning Geo. Lindsay and I took advantage of the trip to Torrey Pines and discussed at length, both going out and on return, the take-over by the museum of my reptile collection, methods of presentation, records, files, and all the rest. Will have important results, if carried out.

Wednesday, January 23, 1963

At the office this morning.

Conference with Dillin, Sinnott, & Zitlau about the 4-utility transmission line.

Some bibliographic work today.

Dave brought around some visitors late this afternoon: Dr. D G Constantine, a bat expert of the US Dept of Public Health, stationed at Las Cruces, N.M.; W S Murphy DVM of the San Diego Dept of Public Health; and F.A. Babbitt of Western Salt.

Thursday, January 24, 1963

At the office this morning.

Made bibliographic progress today. Prepared working lists for the Natural History and Medical libraries.

Tonight went to Howard Chernoffs for dinner. Saw his new house. Other guests: Peg White, George Gildred, the Lorin Klapps.

Friday, January 25, 1963

At the office this morning. Finished a lot of chores and some shopping.

Got another tier of 3 x 5 card drawers today and spent a lot of time this afternoon fixing them up, and transferring cards. At last the 3 x 5 cards are no longer so crowded that one can see what the cards contain.

Today I took the map (range maps) to Kobler for copying, the work to be done outside of business hours and charged to me.

Tonight went to a Los Angeles Philharmonic concert. The first part was fine; the last modern and not to my liking.

Saturday, January 26, 1963

A lot of miscellaneous clean-up work today. I was as active as my fading energy permits, but bibliographies progress was small.

Joe Copp worked this afternoon in the library. Also until late tonight.

Sunday, January 27, 1963

Worked on income tax until 2PM. Gathered most of the raw material. Also worked on my library index cards, which haven't been filed for a long time.

Joe Copp started work at noon and worked until about 7.

Made progress on card filing; worked until tired out at 8PM. It is a lot more pleasant to file with plenty of room in each drawer.

Monday, January 28, 1963

Got up this morning at 2 and did a little work on the card file. Got a second good sleep from 3 on.

Solar directors meeting from 9 to 11:30. then to Gas Co office where Sherwin and I had a conference with Hi on various matters until 12:30.

Finished the filing of 3x5 cards tonight; up to date for the first time in a long time.

Tuesday, January 29, 1963

This morning worked from 2:30 until 5:20 on the preliminary draft of a talk to be made at the Santa Fe Ranch conference next Saturday on some factors in public relations.

At the office this morning.

This was another disappointing day. I had hoped to finish the Santa Ranch talk for Saturday but a lot of things came up unexpectedly and progress in this was poor. Particularly there were a lot of calls about a protest at the City Council meeting concerning a controversial book on the Public Library shelves -- The Temptations of Christ, a novel by a Greek novelist.

This involved a lot of time with many interruptions. At least I did get done some work not requiring stead application, namely the filing of a large accumulation of pamphlets. At last, for the first time in many weeks, I am up to date with all pamphlets, as well as their index cards, all filed down to date.

Wednesday, January 30, 1963

At the office this morning. made some progress with the Rancho Santa Fe talk, but then went over to the library for a conference with Moore about the controversial book. But Moore didn't show up so I drafted a letter to City Manager Fletcher postponing action until the next library commission meeting.

Tonight went over to Gartz Goulds and then to Island's for dinner.

At the office this morning. Worked hard on the Rancho Santa Fe talk; made good progress and almost finished it.

Friday, February 1, 1963

At the office this morning.

Continued work on the Santa Fe Ranch talk. Finished it.

John Sloan came over this afternoon to study the proposal to microfilm the accession records of both collections.

Early this morning I coughed up two blood clots that seemed to come from the spot in my right lung or trachea where I have felt pressure for many years. It seemed to relieve the pressure.

The Gould's came to dinner tonight.

Saturday, February 2, 1963

Only faint blood traces this morning.

Worked on accounts this morning.

Went out to the Gas Co supervisors meeting at Rancho Santa Fe. After lunch delivered my talk on Lessons from the Past. Seemed to go over alright.

The attended one meeting on Communications and another on Public Relations. Being by then pretty tired, I came home.

Joe Copp came in just at that time.

Worked late tonight on accounts.

Sunday, February 3, 1963

This morning went out to Rancho Santa Fe and attended the final meeting of the Gas Co conference from 9 until 12. Then had lunch at the Inn and returned to town.

At the Inn at 8:50 saw a lot of Uta stansburiana very active in vines along a rock wall. It was quite warm. They were very dark in color.

Spent quite a bit of time talking over various problems with Joe Copp this afternoon.

----
Monday Feb 4, continued
with which he disconnected all the lines of the old pump and reconnected them to the new. He had all the tools he needed -- no more and no less. I think the whole job, after he arrived, took only about 3/4 hour.

Drove the car home and left it in Tussey's garage.

What luck that this didn't happen on the road to Santa Fe Ranch!

Pretty well tired out tonight.

Monday, February 4, 1963

This was a lively day.

At the office most of the morning. Expected to have a conference with Hi on P.U.C. affairs but he was tied up with other matters.

Left for Rancho Santa Fe at 11 to make a rattlesnake talk before the Rancho Santa Fe Rotary Club. This seemed to go over quite well. There were about 30 present; I found that 40 would have been much better and will ask for this much if I give it again. A lot of members came up to ask questions at the end. Claude Conklin and Ned Brice were among those present.

I had promised to be back at the office at 2:30 for a possible Executive Committee meeting so I returned to the office, but Hi was still tied up. So, I started for home at about 3:15. Got as far as 9th and E and the car went dead in the middle of the street -- gas pump trouble as it turned out. An embarrassing spot for sure. Phoned the Gas Co 7th street garage and 3 of the boys came over and manhandled me over to the curb, where, fortunately there was a vacant space. Phoned Tussey's garage and a man came down with a new pump, which he installed. I was impressed with the faculty (continued on Sunday Feb 3)

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 07/10/2014 01:25 PM

Tuesday, February 5, 1963

Spent a lot of time this morning suggesting revisions in a letter to the Commission, but it was too late to be of any use; the letter had already been sent. At the office part of the morning, but went over to see Miss Breed at the Library from 9 to 10:30 to discuss the prospective meeting to discuss the controversial book about the Temptation of Christ.

At the medical Library from 1 to 3. Got through with a survey of recent volumes of the American Journal of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene. At 3 I was so tired I had to give up and go home for a rest.

Today got the semi annual report of sales of rattlesnakes for the period 7-1-62 to 12-31-62. There were 75 sets sold. I should guess there remain about that many unsold.

Wednesday, February 6, 1963

At the office this morning.

Today made a start on a subject numbering system.

Went to the SD Co Medical Library at 12:40, immediately after lunch and worked until 3:15, when I was tired out. Cleaned up quite a few items, but it is evident they will hardly have more than half of what I have on the medical list.

Thursday, February 7, 1963

At the office this morning. Had a conference with Sherwin on some organizational problems.

Made headway on some bibliographical items.

Worked at the Medical Library from 12:35 to 2:45 and cleared up the remaining items that they have -- all but 2 items that were loaned out at the time.

Made other bibliographical progress today; I am a little encouraged.

Friday, February 8, 1963

At the office this morning.

Wrote letters.

Tonight went to the Annual Dinner of the San Diego Opera Guild as the guests of the Jess Haugh's at the Coronado Hotel.

Page Edit History:

Saturday, February 9, 1963

Spent the entire day on my personal annual financial statements and almost finished them.

Wasted some time on my Monroe Calculator which was found to be out of order, although I thought it was ok when I put it up on the shelf in the closet, out of the kid's reach.

In the evening went to a party given by Mrs. Hauser at the Valley Ho. We had a some difficulty finding the joint; it was raining - our first good rain since last Spring. The food was good but they allowed the loud speaker which brought in lousy music to play after dinner in our private dining room with the result that it was impossible to hear anything that anybody said. Got home about 11.

Joe Copp worked on his sidewinders in our basement today.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 07/10/2014 01:29 PM
  • ARobbins 02/12/2014 01:54 PM

Sunday, February 10, 1963

Joe Copp worked virtually all day in the basement on his sonoran sidewinder problem.

Took Sabin Type 3 Oral Polio-vaccine this afternoon.

Tuesday, February 12, 1963

This morning a man named Pancake, a wheat rancher from Kansas called up and told me at great length about a cure for rattler bite they used extensively on animals in Kansas and Nebraska. The antidote contains nitric acid, sulfuric acid, camphor, and turpentine -- relative amounts not stated. Got down at the office nearly an hour late.

Had a talk with Hi Dillin about his conference yesterday with the Commission on passing on to the electric customers the reduction in gas fuel cost. Went out and got a key to the Natural History Library; also ordered a book by Bellairs.

At 12:10 met Charles C. Camp the paleontologist with his wife and another lady at the Zoo. Took them to lunch; we had a very interesting chat. Large crowd because of the school holiday.

Went to the Natural History Museum (1:30) Library and worked there until 4:30. Accomplished quite a lot; cleared up a lot of items. Pretty tired when I quit.

Friday, February 15, 1963

At the office for a short time. Turned over to Hi his letter to the stockholders to be contained in the annual report. Made a few mino's suggestions.

Then went over to the library where we had a commission meeting that lasted from 10 to 12. After completing the regular business of the commission we proceeded with a discussion of the retention or suppression of the controversial book "The Last Temptation of Christ" a novel by Nikos Kazantzkes. There were about 15 outsiders present, including the newspaper reporters. 6 or 8 people spoke, There were 3 who took a strong religious stand against the book, and 3 others, who while not liking all aspect of this book, objected to censorship in all its forms. Miss Breed told at length of the library's selection policy.

The Commission decided not to restrict the use of the book in any way; at least this was the recommendation to be made to the City Manager.

Miscellaneous work this afternoon and evening.

Got in some good licks making a schedule of scale counts from the various recent pamphlets I had set aside. This will enable me readily to pick new mins and maxes.

On the whole a satisfactory day with something accomplished.

Saturday, April 13, 1963

This morning worked on the angelensis description and made progress although not nearly so much as I had hoped.

In the afternoon made counts on the Dixon, Sabbath, and Worthington specimens from the University of Kansas. There were 5 specimens and I finished with them. The D, S, & W scale counts which had set new records were all found in error except one so that only a new scutulatus ventral male record was set and this only by 1.

Eleanor and Vic called this afternoon.

Friday, April 26, 1963

Left Palm Springs this morning at 8:45. There were some sprinkles of rain. Arrived at El Centro branch of San Diego State College at 11:20; 123 miles.

Met Dr. Hikeda, Director of the State College and Mrs. Maurine Gay the Librarian.

Went to a meeting of the El Centro Kiwanis Club at noon where I gave the Rattlesnake talk. Got the usual service club deal; they had promise me 40 minutes, including 5 for questions but I got a little less than 25 and couldn't make a satisfactory talk. Usual introductions and life histories of 4 new members took more than 15 minutes. And announcements. I don't exaggerate the importance of rattlesnakes, but they shouldn't promise more than they can deliver and thus ruin the speakers presentation.

In the afternoon from 2 to 4 went to an autographing party at the Libraries of San Diego State College and Imperial Valley Junior College. Signed 3 sets altogether. They had more new ones (I don't know where they got them - but no sale. Time spent mostly chatting with visitors.

Home via Highway 80. Very windy and some sprinkles of rain. Started at 4:15; arrived at 6:50. 127 miles. Total for the trip 397 miles.

Saturday, April 27, 1963

Went down to 1st & Ivy Garage & got the Cad which was repaired while we were away.

Went to a meeting of a proposed advisory board (not yet formed) of the Salk Institute of Biological Studies. First met at Valencia Hotel, then out to the buildings now under construction on the site, which is northwest of the new U.C. Campus. We had an exceedingly interesting meeting with discussion of the plans for the Institute by Salk, Walker Cisler and others From 10:30 at the hotel to 3:30 at the site. Besides Cisler who I had known in EEI days, I met Don Kennedy of Oklahoma City, Pres. Hotchkiss and a number or others both from in town and out of town whom I had known before, It was a decidedly worth-while affair.

Called at Philips on the way home, for my gas Co. mail.

Saturday, May 4, 1963

Today I worked on the closely related problems of maps, tables of geographical distribution, and synonymies, and made some real progress.

Got two new and important papers from Parrish Also an inquiry from the National Institutes of Health concerning Carl Gans' request for a research grant for a study of "The Functional Morphology of the Vipered Feeding Mechanism" This will be a time-consuming job to answer.

Continued with mapping all day and evening; and as far as I know all the maps] have been corrected for second. Could proceed to have all changes made, but of course I have no idea what new specimens might come to hand and require further changes. So this will have to be delayed until last minute for it would never do to have the maps changed twice, a formidable job in any case.

A Historical Note: Heard from Benny Banta today and he gave me dates from the Cal Acad Assession books.

The date when I went out with Van Denburgh and Slevin and picked up the ring neck on the Ballena Grade near Witch Creek was May 9, 1923; and the date when we went to Mountain Springs and they (not I) discovered the rock-flake method of catching Xantusia Henshawi was May 13, 1923.

Monday, June 10, 1963

Almost had an accident this morning but fortunately there was none. It was at 6th & Juniper at about 8:30. I had stopped at this corner and was preparing to turn south. Several cars passed going south; I was waiting for the last one to pass. When it had gone by, I started my car slowly and was preparing to turn south. Meanwhile a man had out passed a car that was parked at the curb. I didn't see him as my eyes were looking right. He jumped out from in front of my car. He wasn't touched, but he was awful mad. Said I should have my eyes examined. Demanded to see my driver's license, which I final showed him. I don't think my bumper came within a foot of him. There was a gardener working in the parking strip.

At the office this morning. Wrote some letters.

Meeting of the directors Natural History Museum, 4 to 5:15.

Trots continued, not much pep.

  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:06 PM

Friday, August 9, 1963

At the office this morning.

Today I got methods and procedures lined up in better shape for producing and having available for reference the two parts of a manuscript for Second:
1) Changes in First to produce the body of second
2) The manuscripts for the Supplement. This sounds simple but thus far it has been very complicated to line up the changes and keep track of what's been finished. Also to keep the finished parts available for references. Maybe at last I'm really on my way.

Got the galley proof of the angelensis paper from the Natural History Museum today.

Worked in the basement this afternoon sorting out rattlers that had been lying around for a long time.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 03/05/2014 05:17 PM

Sunday, August 11, 1963

Worked early this morning on the data for the hybrid rattlesnakes. This is ging to require more checking than I had supposed.

Also some work on the hemipenes of angelensis. I doubt whether it will be advisable to mention these in the angelensis paper, the gallery proof of which must be returned to the museum next week.

Went over to Cottons at 11:15 for a buffet lunch and a piano recital by Lioll Barber. Very enjoyable. Returned via the Park where GG was dropped for a Globe Theatre production, at 2:30.

A party by the name of Folsom with a snake show at Hermosa Beach called up to tell me of some unusual rattlers he had including what he thinks is a stephensi-scutulatus hybrid from west of the Panamints (it is almost colorless); a freak viridis or lutosus with a queer pattern; a tzabcan from Yucatan; and edwardsi from New Mexico. He said he might bring them down in a couple of weeks or a UCLA parasitologist would, for photographing. He said he would let me or Chuck Shaw know if he came so we could alert the photographer. He is going to Arizona next week.

(See Aug. 10)

This is very gratifying to me, coming as it does from the Keeper of the entire Zoological Dept. of the British Museum for many years; a man who specialized in reptiles.

Thursday, September 5, 1963

Pretty sore this morning.

Before going down to the office, I went out to the Internal Revenue Office on Ohio St and turned in the material I had prepared last weekend. The man who was supposed to interview me had a previous engagement so I went down to the office, where I got a few things done.

The internal revenue man called up and I made a date to see him at 1:30.

Went over to Potter's the letter-head engravers and ordered a full supply of letter paper and envelopes. I wonder whether this was wise at my age.

Went out to the Internal Revenue Office to see Mr. Giannengeli. I found that he did not have my prior returns, not even 1962, that they were questioning; they have not been send down fro Los Angeles. I gave him copies. I found he had gone over the material I submitted this morning and his present interest seemed to be the herpetological collection of specimen and how the value was arrived at. I left him copies of the letters from the other museums setting values and he is to notify me when he wishes to see me again.

Tuesday, September 10, 1963

Kauffeld is in town. Will lunch with him Thursday

Continued work on Chapter 4, mostly correcting the Xerox sheets that will show the change to be made in the printed part of the First Printing

Tuesday, October 8, 1963

This was TV day.

Went over to the Zoo at 9:10 and worked until 11:50 on what was to be a 7-1/2 minute episode (released some day in the future) on Zoorama, this one to be on the Rattlesnake's rattle. There were several retakes, none any too good, and I was quite warm and when they were finished. Too much standing up for me.

I was amazed at the number of men and the extent of the equipment required for this minor affair.

There was no preposed script, although it was more or less made definite in the several tryouts. I had originally expected that the program was to be based on questions that Chuck Shaw would propound to me; however this scheme wasn't followed. The script, to whatever extent it can be said they had one, was based on preliminary chatter that I gave them -- incidental information on rattles and their use -- before we got down to business.

Went to the office for half an hour at noon, then came home all tuckered out.

Saturday, October 19, 1963

Worked all day on the Population Explosion paper and think it was improved in some details.

Gave the paper tonight at Scholia. It took exactly 45 minutes. There were 14 present besides myself; the only visitor was Bill Lacey.

I think it went OK judging from the discussion, which lasted nearly an hour My rebuttal took 10 minutes. 9:45 to 9:55.

Jansen and Leonard were the most critical of the paper.

Most of them seemed satisfied with the explanations in the rebuttal.

As usual I was tired and sopping wet when the meeting was over.

A lot of members I particularly wished to have present were not there.

Friday, October 25, 1963

Woke up today with an unpleasant attack of cystitis. Called up Dr. Gerald Howes office and made an appointment for 3 o'clock this afternoon.

At the office for a short time this morning but left at about 10:45. Feeling prey lousy. Passed several gobs that looked like scabs.

Did a little carding this morning.

Finally got in the see Dr. Howe at 4 PM. Diagnosis was cystitis, somewhat worse than the attack of July 1962. He prescribed the same medicine, so I will be able to use up what was left last time. Next appointment Nov. 1 at 11:15. If I am uncomfortable next Monday, I am to call him then.

At last I have received a letter from Jennings at the U.C. Press. He is resigning to go into architecture. No successor mentioned. This is very bad news for me, as I shall have to start fresh with a new editor, really hard luck. Jennings' and I had worked out a lot of methods for the revisions.

Sloan did some scale counting today I didn't know he was doing it so exercised no supervision. He counted the 7 new gloydi.

Wednesday, October 30, 1963

At the office until 11 this morning.

Then went out to La Mesa. Left in plenty of time but got completely lost and didn't get to the Rotary Club until 12:45. I went all over the damn county -- way up to some of the houses on narrow roads in Grossmont -- finally located the Rotary Club, where I was to talk at 12:45. I thought they would be frantic, but they weren't troubled in the least. Of course I got no lunch. It was their 38th anniversary meeting.

I talked on rattlesnakes and it seemed to go over OK. I told them I would leave 5 to 7 minutes for question, so I quit at 1:25, but their questions continued until about 1:40.

Came back to town with an old-timer who wanted to be taken to the Bank of America, which is where I dropped him.

At lunch at home; pretty tired. I have dropped the pink pills as they seem to give me indigestion.

Friday, November 1, 1963

At the office until 10:30 this morning.

Had an appointment with Dr. Howe this morning at 11:15; got there a few minutes late, but still had a short wait. He reported the urine completely cleared up. Made a retention test and also checked the prostate by feel only. Said everything seemed to be OK. Continue to take the red pills for 3 more days. Come in for a check-up at the end of 3 months (this would make it Feb. 1) or come in at once if cystitis flared up again.

Gas Co turned furnace pilots and checked water heater today.

Did accounts this afternoon.

Worked on gloydi characters tonight. It now looks as if gloydi would be invalid.

Saturday, November 2, 1963

Worked all day on the gloydi-intermedius problem and decided not to retract the recognition of gloydi not withstanding in 5 out of 32 cases the postnasal touches both the first and second supralabials, which is the case in intermedius intermedius. This decision was a great relief; I hated the idea of going back and reversing the decisions already made. Maybe I will find some other differences which I doubt. All of this required a lot of checking and tabulating.

At 4:15 went out to the 50th anniversary of the Elli Barrons in the Sweetwater Valley. Got lost and had a hard time finding the place, but finally made it. Got home at 7.

Monday, November 4, 1963

At the office this morning.

Today I got started again on hybrids and made some real progress, at least on lining up the work. Found the six broods of the scutulatus-unicolor series that were born subsequent to the publication of First; now I will count their scales in the prefrontal area and body blotches.

Tonight Shaw bought over the hybrids from near Rose Canyon and Dripping Springs. We had expected to use a new anesthetic on them so as to make scale counts. It was finally decided to pickle them instead, which is fine with me as this will permit more accurate examinations.

Thursday, November 7, 1963

Today I attended a meeting of the Smog advisory committee from 9:30 to 11:30 to discuss our recommendations to the Board of Supervisors as to the adoption of the rule requiring crank case devices on secondhand cars and also instituting a state inspection system. Voted to recommend both to the Supervisors, also the writer was to set forth the reasons at the Supervisors Meeting scheduled for Nov. 25.

Then to the office for a shot time.

Tonight went to a San Francisco Opera Co presentation of Falstaff. Don't think I even heard this opera before. Pleasurable music with no catching areas. Showed the Verdi touch in many phrases.

The cast included Geraint Evans as Falstaff, Mary Costa as Mistress Ford, Janis Martin as Meg, Thomas Stewart at Ford, and others equally good.

Fortunately we did not go to a preliminary dinner, so the schedule was not too hectic.

This afternoon I counted the scales in the prefrontal area and the body blotches on the scutulatus-unicolor hybrid series and can now proceed with statistical computations.

Saturday, November 16, 1963

This morning I left the motel a little before 10. Went shopping and succeeded in finding the little surplus store where I had obtained some plain black cotton socks last year or the year before. This is the army or navy surplus store, a tiny hole in the hall at 546 S. Main. Anyway I got a dozen pair, and was pleased to have found the place.
Then went to the public library, when I arrive at 10:50. Worked until 1:30 by which time I was so tired I had to quit. Got home at 2:15.

I cleaned up a number of biological abstracts stems and several others of some importance, particularly one on photographing the strike of a rattlesnake.

Rested the remainder of the afternoon. GG brought Bertha Polland in. She tried to get a seat for tonight but had no luck.

Ate at Carls. Everything was peaceful tonight; no crowd.
the opera Forza del Destino was excellent. The cast included Leontyne Price as Leonona, James McCracker as Alraro, Julian Haas as Carlo, Walker Kreppel as Guandians, and Elfego Esparza as Melitone. Same conductor as last night.

Price was in tune for m; the audience was most enthusiastic.

Got home at 12:10.

Spent a lot of time at TV and radio. The news of the shooting of Oswald is simply incredible.

Worked on smog problems even though the Board of Supervisors meeting has been indefinitely postponed.

Herb Kunzel called up to say that the Solar meeting would be held tomorrow morning

Went to a cocktail party and buffet supper at the Barrett's at La Jolla. Drove out with May Johnson in her new Plymouth station wagon. A very pleasant party with good food.

Monday, November 25, 1963

Solar board meeting this morning, 9 to 11; then to the office until noon. Looked around some proposed plant changes at Solar.

Did considerable card filing today.

  • pamg 03/07/2014 01:02 PM

Tuesday, November 26, 1963

Got up at 2:30 this morning and worked until 4:30 on card filing. Am now up to date.

At the office this morning. Worked all morning preparing the data for the Smog meeting of the Board of Supervisors, postponed from Nov. 25. In the afternoon I got word the meeting had now been set for 9:30 AM, Dec. 2.

KW directors met here 2:00 to 3:20.

Zoo finance committee followed by Trustees meeting 5:30 to 8:30 PM.

Thursday, November 28, 1963

Thanksgiving dinner for 15 which took from 1 PM until late in the afternoon.

Friday, November 29, 1963

Continued with the smog report and made more progress.

Went up to Les's with GG this morning and spent about 1-1/2 hrs there. Found a black cat locked in one of the rooms. Seem to have lost one of the keys.

Took some photographs in the afternoon.

Today is our 52nd wedding anniversary.

Tonight Philip Regel of U.C.L.A. brought in a C. intermedius intermedius from 5 mi. W of Pachuca, Hidalgo. If it checks out it will be a considerable range extension.

Page Edit History:

Saturday, November 30, 1963

Overhauled the yellow sheets (the Supplement entries) for Chapter 4.

Made complete scale counts of the new intermedius specimen that came in yesterday.

Went up to Les's house for a while.

Other miscellaneous work.

Sunday, December 1, 1963

Dinner tonight at Hotel del Coronado with Kellys and Smiths of Buffalo.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 07/10/2014 03:53 PM

Monday, December 2, 1963

Went to the meeting of the Board of Supervisors this morning from 9:30 to 12:00. I made my report of the recommendations of the Citizens Advisor Committee to the Air Pollution Control Board of S. D. Co.. Took about 15 minutes; I think it went over OK. This was followed by a long discussion, thoroughly covering the proposal for mandatory installation of crank case devices on 1950-1960 cars.

Went home for lunch and then down to the office, where at least I was able to clean up my desk. Then back to the Supervisors meeting which lasted from 2 to 3. They finally voted (3 to 2) to install crank case devices and to authorize state inspection stations.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 03/07/2014 01:19 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:06 PM

Tuesday, December 3, 1963

At the office this morning. Long conference with Dillin on various Company matters.

Took films up to Bunnell's. Will be ready in a week.

Did a little work on getting the data lined up for the Academic Press project. Also a little organizing on hybrids.

Went to a meeting in Borthwick's office to discuss the Otto bequest. This lasted from 5 to 6.

Heard from the new editor who will handle Rattlesnakes: Miss Lucie E. N. Dobbis, Executive Editor, Calif. 94720.

Page Edit History:

Wrote letters.

Spent most of the afternoon on my accounts.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 03/07/2014 01:30 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:06 PM

Thursday, December 5, 1963

At the office this morning until 9:30; then went to a meeting of the Public Utility Commission in the New State Building that lasted from 10 until 12. Commissioner Bennett presided. The meeting was supposed to be for the purpose of outlining the data and methods to be followed in the prospective rate case, but instead it was used as a secondary board to criticize the Company's position on gas rate rebates. The Commission and its attorney belabored the Company for its attitude and praised the opposing City Attorneys for their positions.

Went back to the office in the afternoon 1:15 to 3:15 and participated in discussion of the morning's proceedings.

Went to Old Timers Dinner tonight. Got home at 9:30. It was a satisfactory affair, but I was rather tired because of having no rest this afternoon

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 07/10/2014 03:54 PM
  • pamg 03/07/2014 01:36 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:06 PM

Friday, December 6, 1963

This morning went to Radio Station KGB and had a question and answer period on Smog. The station questioner was Fred Lewis and my partner answering questions was Dr. J.B. Askew. He did more answering than I. This lasted from 7:55 to 8:45.

Then to the office. Had a dentist appointment with Dr. Sam T Emery and was in the chair from 9:30 until 11:20. Had a large filling replaced (upper right) and a general clean up. No other bad items were found.

Returned to the office and accomplished miscellaneous items.

Tonight went to a diner meeting of the Zoological Society Research Committee. Saw a lot of friends. Met Dr. Perry Gilbert of Cornell who is a friend of Dr. Wright's.

Found Dr. Fetter favoring the idea of using a part of the Otto money for the San Pasqual breeding farm project. This is a disappointment to me.

The talks at the meeting were by Dr. Michael Pilson on the differences in milk by different animals; and by Stahnke on scorpions. He inevitably got to rattlesnakes and claimed the failures in cryotherapy were due to incorrect techniques in the removal or warming up period of the treatment Home at 10 P.M.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 07/10/2014 03:55 PM

  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:06 PM

Saturday, December 7, 1963

Spent most of the day sharpening up the Campo story for the talk at the Wednesday Club next week. Added a few episodes to fatten it up a little.

Page Edit History:

Sunday, December 8, 1963

Continued work on the Camp talk and improved it a little. This was a sad day as for as accomplishments were concerned; too many conflicting events.

Had 6 people in for lunch: the Kellys from Coronado and Buffalo; Winnie Wright and Lyell Barger; Oscar Cotton and Kathryn McCommon.

Dinner tonight at the Cortez, guests of the Stakeys. Then to a concert of the Los Angeles Symphony: Brahms no 3 and Beethoven No 5. They also ran in an extra something by a modern French-American which sounded like juvenile fun in a boiler factory.

Tuesday, December 10, 1963

In the afternoon Susan de Treville came in to discuss her problem of making an antivenin from King snake blood. We discussed various matters connected with this project from 3:30 until 5.

Went to the animal dinner given by the Gas Co Women's Committee tonight. A fairly pleasant time and good food. Was at the Palm Room, US Grant. Home at 9:15.

Gave the Campo talk at the Wednesday Club. I think it went OK; they seemed to like it. There was a full house. Later [Miss breed]] offered to mimeograph it.

Pretty tired this afternoon, as I always am after talk of this kind.

John Sloan came over for the Natural History Museum with a few problems this afternoon at 4.

Saturday, December 14, 1963

Finished up all the Christmas Cards and arranged the order of mailings. Mailed all of those outside of California.

Started work on the keys for the Academic Press paper and found they are going to be more difficult that I expected. Will probably have to split the territorially as they are in Rattlesnakes.

Allen came in to talk business for about an hour this morning.

Received 4 small rattlers as a loan from the University of Kansas, 2 lepidus klauberi from Sinaloa, and two that are probably trireriatus triseriatua from Mexico (state) and Morelos.

Went to Scholia tonight; Larry Cook talked on the history of cartography.

Meeting of the Zoo Financial Committee and Board of Trustees 5:30 to 8:30.

Another bad day in which nothing was accomplished toward the Academic Press project or Rattlesnakes, Ed. 2. This seems to be characteristic of these days around the holidays, a very discouraging situation.

A Tribune reporter interviewed me at length this afternoon about the 1916 flood.

Chuck Wagon

Midway Chuck Wagon
Midway Drive at Rosecrans
San Diego 6, Calif.

Delicious choice of prime ribs -- all you can eat for $2.29 is the slogan of the Midway Chuck Wagon. Customers are invited to dine "Chuck Wagon Style" in a quaint Western atmosphere. Enjoy your favorite cocktails in the unique Gaslight Bar or the Longbranch Saloon where top names in the entertainment world will entertain you. The policy of giving the people what they want in quality... price... and service... has made the Midway Chuck Wagon the outstanding eating and entertainment attraction of the West.
